{
  "doc_id": "14359",
  "text": "The first step of the G1-arrest pathway is a rapid rise in the p53 protein level [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Multiple regulatory links between ATM and p53 have been shown. First of all, ATM phosphorylates p53 directly [CITATION_3] . Secondly, ATM-dependent activated Chk2 phosphorylates p53 on another specific site [CITATION_4] . This interferes with the binding with Mdm2, a protein that exports p53 out of the nucleus for ubiquitination and degradation. Thirdly, ATM targets Mdm2 directly and modifies its activity [CITATION_5] . Thereby p53 accumulates in the nucleus mainly by stabilization. In addition, histone acetyltransferase p300 increases p53 transcription by an additional acetylation of p53 [CITATION_6] .",
